Why the constant  `rexp (-(Ï€ * âˆš3 * (1 / 2)))`? If you assume `1 / 2 â‰¤ Î¾.im` then the best possible bound is clearly `rexp (-Ï€)` which is both a stronger and a simpler statement.

(The reason `âˆš3` seems relevant is because the lemma `exists_one_half_le_im_and_norm_le` is not optimal; it gives us `Î¾` with `1 / 2 â‰¤ Î¾.im`, but actually one can find `Î¾` with `âˆš3 / 2 â‰¤ Î¾.im`, and then we would have `â€–ð•¢ 1 Î¾â€– â‰¤ rexp (-(Ï€ * âˆš3))`. I deliberately omitted the `âˆš3` factor, because the weaker statement is sufficient and makes the arithmetic easier. You seem to have weakened the statement further while at the same time making it more complicated.

(You could for instance show
```
lemma Function.Periodic.qParam_abs_le_of_one_half_le_abs {Î¾ : â„‚} (hÎ¾ : 1 / 2 â‰¤ Î¾.im) :
    â€–ð•¢ 1 Î¾â€– â‰¤ rexp (-Ï€) := by
  rwa [Periodic.qParam, ofReal_one, div_one, Complex.norm_eq_abs, Complex.abs_exp, Real.exp_le_exp,
    mul_right_comm, mul_I_re, neg_le_neg_iff, â† ofReal_ofNat, â† ofReal_mul, im_ofReal_mul,
    mul_comm _ Ï€, mul_assoc, le_mul_iff_one_le_right Real.pi_pos, â† div_le_iffâ‚€' (by norm_num)]
```
Thanks! I was just not thinking enough about it!
